Late night presenter Stephen Colbert welcomed 17-year-old Thunberg to your show on Tuesday and conducted a lengthy interview with the Swede.
She spoke not only about her fight against climate change, but also about her conflict with the powerful in the world.
&quot;There are some things that surprised me,&quot; she said.
&quot;How far people go to take the focus away from the climate crisis,&quot; she was shocked.
She has experienced &quot;everything from organized hate campaigns to threats just because a group of children takes to the streets&quot;.
She finds heads of state and leading politicians who mock her or even try to silence her on social media &quot;funny&quot; because the reactions show her &quot;since they have no other answer to it&quot;.
It became particularly interesting at the end of the interview, when Greta Thunberg was asked about a well-known scene in which she threw a bitter look at US President Trump.
At the 2019 UN Climate Summit in New York, for which the activist sailed across the Atlantic, her expressive gaze was caught by the cameras and has since been seen by countless people on the internet.
The short clip became a GIF, an animated image, which eventually became one of the most used images for Trump opponents.
But what did the 17-year-old think about the US President at that moment?
When asked a relatively open question by Stephen Colbert, she answered only briefly and dryly: &quot;To be honest, I don&#39;t think that needs any further explanation&quot;.
The experienced satirist Colbert had probably not expected the quick-witted answer and disappeared from the picture with a short laugh.
With her &quot;How dare you?&quot; speech on the principles of climate protection, she was remembered by many at the climate conference.
