Fleetwood Mac co-founder Peter Green has died
His life has been a roller coaster ride: after a rapid rise with Fleetwood Mac, it went steeply downhill and then slowly up again.
Blues rock guitarist Peter Green has died at the age of 73.
Brilliant guitarist, drug junkie, cult follower: Fleetwood Mac co-founder Peter Green is dead.
He died peacefully in his sleep at the age of 73, family members said in an official statement on Saturday, with further statements expected in the coming days.
Top musicians like Peter Frampton recognized Green as one of the best blues and rock guitarists.
In an emotional response, Mick Fleetwood spoke of a &quot;monumental loss&quot; for all members of Fleetwood Mac, past and present.
The drummer Fleetwood and the guitarist Green founded the now legendary band in London in 1967. His dreamy instrumental hit &quot;Albatross&quot; is still unforgettable today.
The musician&#39;s life (&quot;The End Of The Game&quot;, &quot;In The Skies&quot;) was like a roller coaster ride.
Green experienced a rapid rise with Fleetwood Mac - but the band then celebrated their greatest successes without him.
Among other things, there is said to have been a dispute because Green wanted to donate all the group&#39;s profits to charity.
He began to appear in loose robes and with a large crucifix.
Mental health problems are also said to have played a role.
Green left the band in 1970, just three years after its formation.
Social decline followed.
The blues-rock guitarist suffered from substance abuse and schizophrenia, according to biographers.
For a long time, Green was treated in psychiatry.
For much of the 1970s, the musician disappeared from the scene.
He is said to have lived on the streets at times, worked as a cemetery gardener and spent a time on an Israeli kibbutz.
Green was born in 1946 into a Jewish working-class family in London&#39;s Bethnal Green.
From a young age he was enthusiastic about US blues musicians such as BB King and Muddy Waters.
At the age of eleven he learned his first guitar moves.
At the age of 15, the teenager began playing guitar professionally and five years later got the chance to be on stage as the lead guitarist for the instrumental band Peter B&#39;s Looners.
A little later he was hired as a replacement for his idol Eric Clapton at the Bluesbreakers.
In the summer of 1967, in the midst of the blues boom, Green formed Fleetwood Mac with fellow Bluesbreakers Mick Fleetwood and John McVie.
Green&#39;s song &quot;Albatross&quot; gave the group their first number 1 hit in the winter of 1968/69 and catapulted them to the top of the British music scene.
But the rapid rise soon showed its downsides: Green couldn&#39;t cope with the media hype, his experiments with the drug LSD became more and more extreme.
He later commented on life between music and addiction in an interview: &quot;The worst thing that has happened to me in life are the drugs - the best thing was to land a number 1 hit&quot;.
Towards the end of the decade, Green achieved a surprise hit in 1979 with an album inspired by religious themes.
Fleetwood Mac meanwhile swam in a new formation on a wave of success without him.
Their 1977 album Rumors sold more than 40 million copies worldwide.
Despite various small solo successes, Green did not make a major comeback until he started again in 1996 with a group of musician friends.
At the time, the British &quot;Daily Telegraph&quot; spoke of a rock star who had returned to earth.
Drug free, Green released a few albums with the Peter Green Splinter Group until the band broke up in 2004.
For music experts, he was already a blues legend during his lifetime - and with his gentle sound one of the most influential guitarists of the past decades.
